eforms, where these spaces of democratic dissent were preempted. The key difference between the two regimes, Nair suggests, is not in the withdrawal of a prolabor state from its protective and regulatory role, as has been argued by many, but rather in the rise of a new kind of state that became functionally decentralized, economically predatory, and politically communalized. These changes, Nair concludes, successfully de-democratized labor politics in India.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aIndustrial relationsxHistoryx20th centuryxIndia. 0aIndustrial relationszIndiaxHistoryy20th century. 0aLabor movementxPolitical aspectsxHistoryx20th centuryxIndia. 0aLabor movementxPolitical aspectszIndiaxHistoryy20th century. 0aLabor policyxHistoryx20th centuryxIndia. 0aLabor policyzIndiaxHistoryy20th century. 0aLabor unionsxHistoryx20th centuryxIndia. 0aLabor unionszIndiaxHistoryy20th century. 4aAnthropology and Archaeology : Ethnography. 4aAsian Studies : India and South Asian Studies. 4aHistory : History. 4aHistory : Industrial / Labor Relations. 4aSociology : Sociology of Work. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Labor & Industrial Relations.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143846247940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438462479423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438462479/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles